{"parse":{"title":"Purple prose","pageid":1528526,"revid":860126500,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">This article is about the literary term. For the album by Deep Purple, see <a href=\"/wiki/Purple_Passages\" title=\"Purple Passages\">Purple Passages</a>.</div>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Literary_criticism\" title=\"Literary criticism\">literary criticism</a>, <b>purple prose</b> is <a href=\"/wiki/Prose\" title=\"Prose\">prose</a> text that is so extravagant, ornate, or flowery as to break the flow and draw excessive attention to itself.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Purple prose is characterized by the excessive use of adjectives, adverbs, and <a href=\"/wiki/Metaphor\" title=\"Metaphor\">metaphors</a>. When it is limited to certain passages, they may be termed <b>purple patches</b> or <b>purple passages</b>, standing out from the rest of the work.\n</p><p>Purple prose is criticized for desaturating the meaning in an author's text by overusing melodramatic and fanciful descriptions. As there is no precise rule or absolute definition of what constitutes purple prose, deciding if a text, passage, or complete work has fallen victim is a somewhat subjective decision. According to <a href=\"/wiki/Paul_West_(writer)\" title=\"Paul West (writer)\">Paul West</a>, \"It takes a certain amount of sass to speak up for prose that's rich, succulent and full of novelty. Purple is [widely seen as] immoral, undemocratic and insincere; at best artsy, at worst the exterminating angel of depravity.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Origins\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Origins</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Examples\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Examples</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origins\">Origins</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Purple_prose&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Origins\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The term <i>purple prose</i> is derived from a reference by the Roman poet <a href=\"/wiki/Horace\" title=\"Horace\">Horace</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-Nixon_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Nixon-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Macrone1994_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Macrone1994-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> (Quintus Horatius Flaccus, 65\u20138 BC) who wrote in his <i><a href=\"/wiki/Ars_Poetica_(Horace)\" title=\"Ars Poetica (Horace)\">Ars Poetica</a></i> (lines 14\u201321):<sup id=\"cite_ref-horace_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-horace-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<blockquote>\n<table class=\"nowrap\">\n\n<tbody><tr valign=\"top\">\n<td style=\"padding-right:2em\"><i>Inceptis grauibus plerumque et magna professis<br /><b>purpureus</b>, late qui splendeat, unus et alter<br />adsuitur pannus, cum lucus et ara Dianae<br />et properantis aquae per amoenos ambitus agros<br />aut flumen Rhenum aut pluuius describitur arcus;<br />sed nunc non erat his locus. Et fortasse cupressum<br />scis simulare; quid hoc, si fractis enatat exspes<br />nauibus, aere dato qui pingitur?</i>\n</td>\n<td>Weighty openings and grand declarations often<br /> Have one or two <a href=\"/wiki/Purple#Royalty\" title=\"Purple\"><b>purple</b></a> patches tacked on, that gleam<br /> Far and wide, when <a href=\"/wiki/Diana_(mythology)\" title=\"Diana (mythology)\">Diana</a>'s grove and her altar,<br /> The winding stream hastening through lovely fields,<br /> Or the river <a href=\"/wiki/Rhine\" title=\"Rhine\">Rhine</a>, or the rainbow\u2019s being described.<br /> There\u2019s no place for them here. Perhaps you know how<br /> To draw a cypress tree: so what, if you\u2019ve been given<br /> Money to paint a sailor plunging from a shipwreck<br /> In despair?<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n</blockquote>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Examples\">Examples</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Purple_prose&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Examples\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Liz Bureman explains purple prose while intentionally using purple prose in the explanation itself:\n</p>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303468\">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><p>On occasion, one finds oneself immersed in the literary throes of a piece of prose where there is very little in the way of advancement of the plot or development of the characters, but the pages are still filled with words. Since the esteemed author has allowed their writing to take a turn for the dry and dull, they gallantly attempt to overcompensate for the lack of stimulation by indulging in elaborate turns of phrase.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p></blockquote>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Purple_prose&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Bulwer-Lytton_Fiction_Contest\" title=\"Bulwer-Lytton Fiction Contest\">Bulwer-Lytton Fiction Contest</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Description\" title=\"Description\">Description</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Euphuism\" title=\"Euphuism\">Euphuism</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Order_of_the_Occult_Hand\" title=\"Order of the Occult Hand\">Order of the Occult Hand</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Purple_prose&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.wordsmith.org/words/purple_prose.html\">\"A Word a Day \u2013 purple prose\"</a>. <i>Wordsmith.org</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">26 December</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Wordsmith.org&amp;rft.atitle=A+Word+a+Day+%E2%80%93+purple+prose&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.wordsmith.org%2Fwords%2Fpurple_prose.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APurple+prose\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">West, Paul (15 December 1985). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/15/books/in-defense-of-purple-prose.html?pagewanted=2\">\"IN DEFENSE OF PURPLE PROSE\"</a>. <i>New York Times</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">26 December</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=IN+DEFENSE+OF+PURPLE+PROSE&amp;rft.date=1985-12-15&amp;rft.aulast=West&amp;rft.aufirst=Paul&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F1985%2F12%2F15%2Fbooks%2Fin-defense-of-purple-prose.html%3Fpagewanted%3D2&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APurple+prose\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Nixon-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Nixon_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Nixon, Cheryl (2008-12-30). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=XTY6q_hIa90C&amp;pg=PA194\"><i>Novel Definitions</i></a>. Broadview Press. pp.&#160;194\u2013. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781770482074\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9781770482074\">9781770482074</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">19 May</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Novel+Definitions&amp;rft.pages=194-&amp;rft.pub=Broadview+Press&amp;rft.date=2008-12-30&amp;rft.isbn=9781770482074&amp;rft.aulast=Nixon&amp;rft.aufirst=Cheryl&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DXTY6q_hIa90C%26pg%3DPA194&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APurple+prose\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Macrone1994-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Macrone1994_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Macrone, Michael (1994-05-18). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=-ohlxXHpEK8C&amp;pg=PA147\"><i>It's Greek to Me</i></a>. HarperCollins. pp.&#160;147\u2013. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780062720443\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780062720443\">9780062720443</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">19 May</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=It%27s+Greek+to+Me&amp;rft.pages=147-&amp;rft.pub=HarperCollins&amp;rft.date=1994-05-18&amp;rft.isbn=9780062720443&amp;rft.aulast=Macrone&amp;rft.aufirst=Michael&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D-ohlxXHpEK8C%26pg%3DPA147&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APurple+prose\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-horace-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-horace_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Horace (18 BC). Ars Poetica. Lines 14\u201321.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">HORATII FLACCI ARS POETICA - epistulae 3 - <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.yorku.ca/pswarney/Texts/ars-poetica.htm\">Translated by A. S. Kline</a>, 2005</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>Alternative translation</i>: \"Your opening shows great promise, and yet flashy<br /><b>purple</b> patches; as when describing<br />a sacred grove, or the altar of <a href=\"/wiki/Diana_(mythology)\" title=\"Diana (mythology)\">Diana</a>,<br />or a stream meandering through fields,<br />or the river <a href=\"/wiki/Rhine\" title=\"Rhine\">Rhine</a>, or a rainbow;<br />but this was not the place for them. If you can realistically render<br />a cypress tree, would you include one when commissioned to paint<br />a sailor in the midst of a shipwreck?\"</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Bureman, Liz. \u201cHow to Know If Your Prose Is Purple.\u201d The Write Practice, Wordpress, 20 Jan. 2014, thewritepractice.com/purple-prose/. Accessed 1 Mar. 2017.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<ul><li>Coles Editorial Board, Dictionary of Literary Terms, Rama Brothers, 2001.</li></ul>\n<table role=\"presentation\" class=\"mbox-small plainlinks sistersitebox\" style=\"background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<td class=\"mbox-image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg/40px-Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"40\" class=\"noviewer\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg/60px-Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg/80px-Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg.p